22 Aug 2012
Though many seem to have missed their targets, the effect was to drive tens of thousands of people to the refugee centres on the border with Turkey, where 70,000 Syrian have already fled, or to other villages and towns.
In corners, some few men remain – mostly FSA, along with a few supporters – out of a population of 20-30,000. "There are six families here, from 2,000," said Mazen Afash, 23, one of them. He was in his repair-shop for motorbikes, now a vital form of transport for rebels in rural areas.
"My family have gone. The women here have mostly fled to Marta, a village six kilometres away. The smaller villages are in less danger than the towns."
He is right. In the last two weeks, a new menace has been added to the shelling or occasional attack from ground forces – now, in any case, tied up in the siege of Aleppo city. Fighter jet attacks, used sporadically before, are being used to intimidate the rebels and their supporters across the province.
A double strike on residential areas in nearby Aazaz last week killed 50 civilians, the worst single such attack of the war. But other towns also suffer sporadic and apparently irrational raids, a bomb or two at a time, not intense enough or accurate enough to further any military purpose but terrifying local populations.
One – a single bomb, falling apparently harmlessly – hit the countryside outside Anadan the morning the Daily Telegraph visited. Another landed in a field next to an outdoor swimming pool used by local teenagers, but empty at the time, outside the town of Mari last week. The town of Tal Rifaat has been singled out for repeated aerial assault.
Each raid is followed by a new surge of arrivals at the refugee camps on the border with Turkey, women and children loaded into farm vehicles with what possessions they can muster, packing the country lanes.
The regime has little sympathy towards this area, and the feeling is mutual. These towns took part in the Muslim Brotherhood uprising against President Hafez al-Assad in the late seventies and early eighties, and many families lost men in that revolt's bloody suppression.
Anadan is home to the political leader of the lead rebel unit fighting in Aleppo, the Liwa al-Tawhid or "Unity Brigade" – the term has both a religious meaning, referring to the Oneness of Allah, and a secular one.
Abdulaziz al-Salameh "Abu Juma'a" was a honey trader before launching his rebellion.
"He's strong, he's fighting for us, he's part of us," said Mustafa Qassem, 20, an FSA man guarding, from no one, a junction in town. "Abu Juma'a was famous for his honey, and we respect him. He is very pious."
Another Anadan native is Abu Juma'a's cousin, Abdulrahman al-Salameh, who heads a battalion of the Jubhat al-Nusra, a much more radical Islamist brigade which denies frequent reports that it is allied to al-Qaeda.
The regime's tactics may be intended to scare the province into submission, the tactic which worked for Hafez al-Assad for so long. But it may just have engendered a reckless, religious, do-or-die bravery.
Out of Anadan's silence, there came a sudden clanking and roaring. There were no regime tanks for miles, but a gun-turret suddenly poked its nose into the square. Bouncing down the road was a captured Russian T55, belching black smoke out of one corner and lurching forwards with difficulty on its half-repaired tracks.
Four young FSA men cheered from its top as it disappeared into the distance, an appropriately Mad Max-style breaking of the silence.
That tank was never going to liberate Damascus, but the MiGs won't tame Aleppo on their own either. The betting must be on more attrition, more flight, more emptied towns before this is over.
