Lewis Hamilton faces Formula One battle in 'uncompetitive' car Lewis Hamilton did not expect to start the defence of his first world title from a position of weakness. Shifting gear: Lewis Hamilton's McLaren may not be at full speed at the start of the season Photo: PA	By Andrew Baker 2:00PM GMT 21 Mar 2009
Comments
Champions rarely do. But the mostly dismal form of McLaren during winter test sessions has forced the young Briton's new boss, Martin Whitmarsh, to concede that his cars are highly unlikely to be at the front of the grid for the start of the season-opening Australian Grand Prix next Sunday. "We do not yet have the technical package that will allow our drivers to fight at the front," said Whitmarsh, who replaced Ron Dennis as McLaren's team principal at the start of the month. "In Formula One there is nowhere to hide: that's what makes our sport so demanding and yet so endlessly fascinating."
'Demanding' is the word to pick up on here, and Hamilton, as McLaren's undoubted team leader, will be the one making the demands in the pit lane at Albert Park in Melbourne. A driver with the number 1 on his car does not expect that car to be lost in the midfield. Unlike his main rivals, Kimi Raikkonen, Felipe Massa, Fernando Alonso and Robert Kubica, Hamilton has never driven a poor Formula One car. Jenson Button, the fellow Briton who has emerged, startlingly, as favourite for the season's first race with the new Brawn team, endured dozens of dismal races at the wheel of hopelessly uncompetitive cars in his team's former incarnation as Honda. Related Articles
Teams reject scoring system
20 Mar 2009
Diffuser row to overshadow opener
21 Mar 2009
Exclusive: Mosley all guns blazing
21 Mar 2009
David Coulthard: Button is the driver to watch
20 Mar 2009
Hamilton: New F1 rules are a shame
20 Mar 2009
For Hamilton to climb into a car at the start of a weekend knowing that it has little chance of carrying him to a podium position will be a novel and unwelcome experience. But Whitmarsh, who has known the 24-year-old since he was a child, is aware of the depth of character of his driver, and is confident that he has the determination to prevail. "It has been extraordinary to watch Lewis maturing into a man and a champion," Whitmarsh said. "There is a depth of humanity there that is quite remarkable. Some drivers are nasty bastards, quite impervious to what is going on around them. Lewis is less impervious, but he has been battle-hardened like no other driver of his age."
McLaren's team principal is referring to the season of 2007, in which Hamilton, on the podium in his first nine races, enjoyed an unprecedented introduction to the sport, before a public falling-out with his eminent team-mate, Alonso, and the team's subsequent involvement in a spying scandal. "We all came out of 2007 feeling scarred and battered," Whitmarsh recalled. "But Lewis was more immediately reflective than some of us."
This strength of character, he believes, will have been reinforced by winning the drivers' title. "If he had lost last year he would have had massive, massive pressure," Whitmarsh said. "You know, 'Will he ever win it?' But when you sit with him now you sense the confidence of a champion."
Whitmarsh steered Hamilton's career once the Hertfordshire teenager came under the auspices of McLaren. With Ron Dennis, he picked the teams that their protégé should drive for as he made his way up the ladder through Formula Renault, Formula Three and GP2. The former aerospace engineer has been with McLaren for two decades, and has indelible memories of another great driver whose finest years were spent with the Woking team. "I remember the first time I met Ayrton Senna properly," he said. "We were testing the McLaren MP4-5B. He had spun off the track and ripped the bottom of the chassis out. He knocked on my door and walked in and apologised. You can imagine how I felt... Ayrton Senna, saying sorry to me."
Whitmarsh recalls Senna as a charming individual, who nonetheless never failed to find every opportunity to establish a psychological advantage over his rivals – and his team-mates. "Ayrton was pure intensity," Whitmarsh said. "By comparison, Lewis is a fuller human being, and that is a great strength. There's no doubt that he leads a fuller life, but with that humanity comes some vulnerability."
That vulnerability seems likely to be tested in the early races of this season, as testing form indicates that McLaren are unlikely to be able to push for victories straight away. This is bad news because the sport's governing body, the FIA, have imposed a new rule which dictates that teams may not test between races, which will make it harder for any outfit struggling for pace to evaluate new technological solutions. Whitmarsh remains upbeat and confident in the ability of his engineers and his drivers to get McLaren back to the front. "I'd like Lewis Hamilton to be world champion during my watch," he said. "We begin our season with huge determination to reassert ourselves at the front and we will not rest for a moment until we have done that. Most importantly, we haven't forgotten how to win." Don’t miss on Thursday - The Daily Telegraph’s six-page Formula One special - including profiles of every driver
